{{for|the non-alcoholic beverage of the same name|Mountain Dew}}
{{Orphan|date=May 2016}}

'''Dewshine''' is a term coined for the non-commercial mixture of the beverage [[Mountain Dew]] with alcohol, notably [[methanol]]. Methanol is toxic to humans, and in January 2016 the mixture resulted in the reported deaths of two Tennessee high school students, Logan Stephenson and J. D. Byram.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tennessee Teens Die After Drinking Mountain Dew/Racing Fuel Cocktail|url=http://www.people.com/article/dewshine-mountain-dew-racing-fuel-mix-second-death-tennessee}}</ref> The methanol in this case was believed to come from racing fuel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Health Buzz: Dewshine – a Mix of Mountain Dew and Racing Fuel – Proves Deadly|url=http://health.usnews.com/health-news/health-wellness/articles/2016-01-28/dewshine-a-mix-of-mountain-dew-and-racing-fuel-proves-deadly-in-tennessee}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Racing fuel mixed with soda suspected in Tennessee teens' deaths|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/27/health/tennessee-teenagers-die-dewshine/}}</ref>

