'''Indian childhood cirrhosis''' is a chronic [[liver disease]] of childhood characterised by [[cirrhosis]] of the liver<ref>{{cite journal|author=Editorial|title=Indian childhood cirrhosis: Several dilemmas resolved|journal=Indian J Med Res|volume=128|date=August 2008|pages=93–96|url=http://icmr.nic.in/ijmr/2008/august/editorial1.pdf}}</ref> due to deposition of [[copper]] in the [[liver]].<ref name="pmid9587155">{{cite journal|last=Tanner|first=MS|title=Role of copper in Indian childhood cirrhosis.|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|date=May 1998|volume=67|issue=5 Suppl|pages=1074S-1081S|pmid=9587155}}</ref> It primarily affects children of 1–3 years of age and has a genetic predisposition. It had a very high case fatality in the past<ref>{{cite journal|last=Nayak|first=NC|author2=et.al|title=Indian childhood cirrhosis-A reevaluation of its pathognomonic features and their significance in the light of clinical data and natural history of the disease|url=http://icmr.nic.in/ijmr/2012/december/IJMR%20Classic2.pdf}}</ref> but has eventually become preventable, treatable and is now rare.<ref name="pmid8615370">{{cite journal|last=Pandit|first=A|last2=Bhave|first2= S|title=Present interpretation of the role of copper in Indian childhood cirrhosis.|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|date=May 1996|volume=63|issue=5|pages=830S-5S|pmid=8615370}}</ref>

